## Level 8 → Level 9
**Objective:** Find the only line in `data.txt` that appears exactly
once — all other lines are repeated duplicates.

**Commands Used:**
```bash
sort data.txt                         # sorted lines alphabetically
                                      # not helpful alone

sort data.txt | uniq                  # removed consecutive duplicates
                                      # still showed too many entries

sort data.txt | uniq -c               # added count of each duplicate
                                      # reduced entries significantly
                                      # but still noisy

sort data.txt | uniq -c | grep "^\s*1 "  # filtered for lines with
                                          # count of 1 — worked but
                                          # unnecessarily complex
```

**Cleanest Way:**
```bash
sort data.txt | uniq -u
# sort first so duplicates are adjacent (uniq needs this)
# -u shows ONLY lines that appear exactly once
# direct and clean — no grep needed
```

**Why `sort` is Needed Before `uniq`:**
`uniq` only compares **adjacent lines** — it doesn't scan the
whole file. So if duplicates aren't next to each other it won't
catch them. `sort` groups all identical lines together first,
making `uniq` work correctly.

**What I Learned:**
- `uniq` alone removes consecutive duplicate lines
- `uniq -c` adds a count of how many times each line appears
- `uniq -u` shows only lines that appear exactly once — cleanest
  solution for this type of problem
- `sort` must always come before `uniq` otherwise duplicates that
  aren't adjacent will be missed
- Pipes can be chained — output of sort feeds into uniq

**All `uniq` Flags:**
```bash
uniq file           # remove consecutive duplicate lines
uniq -c file        # show count of each line
uniq -u file        # show only unique lines (appear once)
uniq -d file        # show only duplicate lines (appear more than once)
uniq -i file        # case insensitive comparison
```

**Key Takeaway:**
Always check if the tool you're using has a built in flag for what
you need before building complex chained commands. `uniq -u` does
in one flag what took three chained commands to do manually.
